Rating: 3
Kind of a lot of work for a pretty good cake. The cake itself is not too chocolatey but rich and dense. I made a 3/4 recipe of the frosting as I wasn't making the cupcakes. Not owning a candy thermometer, I boiled the sugar syrup to the hard ball stage and might have overboiled it a little. Also, I only have a hand-power egg beater, and had a lot of difficulty beating in the butter. At the end, it still looked pretty curdled and my arm was about to fall off. What to do, what to do? I ended up whirling small batches in the blender, which whipped it up nicely. I baked the in two 8-in instead of 9-in pans. As a result, the cakes were much more mounded than expected and it took a lot of frosting to fill in the gaps. I hardly had enough left for more than a crumb coat. I ended up mixing together a bit of the old-fashioned butter /powdered sugar/milk frosting and dyed it blue for the decorations. It came out tall, lovely, and delicious, but perhaps not worth all that effort. The frosting is VERY buttery, and if I were to make it again, I'd probably use about 2/3 the butter called for. I'd also slice off the tops of the cakes. A note on the coloring--the frosting did turn out a creamy yellow-white, but so much of the flavor is from the butter--don't replace it with anything else, or you'll end up with sugary car wax.

