Rating: 3
I agree about the frosting color. I make a variaton on the "Wilton" white frosting with a block of Crisco regular shortening, 1 lb. sifted 10X sugar, 2 tea. McCormick's imitation butter (clear) and 2 tea. McCormick's imitation clear vanilla and enough water (start with 1 Tbs.) to make it creamy. It will be white. My family loves it but I secretly prefer the off white "true" buttercream frosting.

Rating: 4
I made this cake just to try it and it was great. Not too rich, not too light. I noticed the comments regarding the frosting....To get really white frosting, you should use shortening and a CLEAR extract....however, when using shortening, you lose the "butter cream" richness, and usually have to increase the sugar added for sweetness. The butter gives the frosting a rich, creamy feel. Use Land O'Lakes UNSALTED butter. You can also add a little bit of wilton white gel or frosting color to it and it will whiten too.

Rating: 4
Yum. My 13 year old daughter and I just made the cake exactly how it was printed for her birthday today and it was delicious. The chocolate flavor was perfect and we were all licking the bowl of the buttercream. It seems some of the reviews were concerned about the frosting not being white enough. Our buttercream was a soft white, and my daughter was able to mix the colors with our gel set and apply the dots herself. She had a great time. We used unsalted butter( I am a big fan of Land O' Lakes) and I am wondering if some of the reviewers used a really yellow colored butter. Even with the addition of vanilla it was a beautiful shade of soft white.

Rating: 0
I haven't made this recipe, but wanted to comment on the yellow buttercream frosting. I took a cake decorating class a while back and was told that the only way to get a true white buttercream frosting is to use shortening and clear vanilla extract. If you used a brown vanilla extract that would have made it even darker. Wilton also makes a clear butter flavored extract that you can add to give it more flavor. Just thought I'd pass along the info.

Rating: 3
The cake was fine and the icing was quite good but the cook from Franklin is dead-on when she says there is no way that this icing is pure white, as pictured. The photo on the cover of the magazine, from where this recipe is printed, is pure fantasy. Clearly a rolled fondant was used to get that smooth finish. Secondly, the colors used in the "dots" come from specialty food gels. Those particular colors are not in the standard food gel kit. The editors of this issue owe their readers a little more! Thankfully the people who use this site are too smart to be fooled by all that stuff.

